# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blue-green-deployment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] In software engineering, **blue–green deployment** is a method of installing changes to a web, app, or database server by swapping alternating production and staging servers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] In blue–green deployments, two servers are maintained: a "blue" server and a "green" server.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] At any given time, only one server is handling requests (e.g., being pointed to by the DNS).
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] For example, public requests may be routed to the blue server, making it the production server and the green server the staging server, which can only be accessed on a private network.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Changes are installed on the non-live server, which is then tested through the private network to verify the changes work as expected.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Once verified, the non-live server is swapped with the live server, effectively making the deployed changes live.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Using this method of software deployment offers the ability to quickly roll back to a previous state if anything goes wrong.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] This rollback is achieved by simply routing traffic back to the previous live server, which still does not have the deployed changes.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] An additional benefit to the blue–green method of deployment is the reduced downtime for the server.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Because requests are routed instantly from one server to the other, there is ideally no period where requests will be unfulfilled.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] The blue–green deployment technique is often contrasted with the canary release deployment technique and it has similarities with A/B testing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Dan North and Jez Humble encountered differences between their test environments and the production environment while running Oracle WebLogic Server for a client sometime around 2005.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] To ensure safe deployment, they introduced a method where the new application version was deployed alongside the live system.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] This approach allowed for thorough testing and easy rollback in case of issues.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] The team initially considered naming these environments A and B but decided against it to avoid the perception that one was primary and the other secondary.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] They instead chose color-based names like blue, green, orange, and yellow, eventually using only blue and green since "having two was sufficient".
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] This naming convention was adopted while working on the original Continuous delivery book published in 2010 and became a common term in the industry afterwards.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Blue–green deployment is widely recognized for its ability to reduce downtime during application updates and minimize the risk of introducing defects into production environments.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] By maintaining two separate environments—blue (the current live environment) and green (the environment with the updated version)—traffic can easily be switched between the two, ensuring that updates are rolled out without disrupting users.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] This method enables quick rollback in case of deployment failure, thus improving overall system resilience and user experience.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] While blue–green deployment reduces risks during updates, it also requires additional resources since two environments need to be maintained simultaneously.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] The cost of running duplicate infrastructure, even temporarily, can be prohibitive for smaller organizations.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Furthermore, complex database migrations may pose challenges, as the system must ensure that both the blue and green environments have consistent data.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Solutions to these issues often involve using database migration tools that allow for backward compatibility between environments.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] There are several approaches to implementing blue–green deployments, each offering varying levels of automation and ease of use depending on the platform and tools available.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] AWS CodeDeploy facilitates blue–green deployments by automating the entire process across services such as Amazon EC2 and AWS Lambda.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] The service shifts traffic between the old (blue) environment and the new (green) environment, minimizing downtime and ensuring a smooth transition.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] AWS CodeDeploy also allows the use of lifecycle event hooks, enabling developers to run tests and verification steps before routing traffic to the green environment.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Kubernetes supports blue–green deployments through its native service capabilities.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Using multiple deployments and services, Kubernetes allows operators to manage traffic routing between blue and green environments with minimal risk of service interruptions.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Tools like ArgoCD or Spinnaker further enhance automation by integrating deployment pipelines directly with Kubernetes clusters.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Google Cloud offers blue–green deployment capabilities through Deployment Manager.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] By defining resources in a declarative format, Deployment Manager allows users to create, update, and delete resources as part of a blue–green deployment process.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Like AWS CodeDeploy, it minimizes downtime by shifting traffic from the old to the new environment after performing necessary tests.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Azure Container Apps provides blue–green deployment capabilities by using container app revisions, traffic weights, and revision labels.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] In this deployment model, two identical environments—referred to as "blue" and "green"—are used.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] The blue environment hosts the current stable version of the application, while the green environment holds the new version.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] Once the green environment is fully tested, production traffic is routed to it, and the blue environment is deprecated until the next deployment cycle.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] To implement blue–green deployment, you create revisions of the container apps and assign traffic weights.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] The blue revision is assigned 100% of the traffic initially, while the green revision is deployed with no production traffic.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] After successful testing of the green revision, the traffic is switched over smoothly without downtime.
[src:blue-green-deployment/blue-green-deployment] If any issues arise in the green environment, a rollback is easily executed, routing traffic back to the blue revision.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:blue-green-deployment/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] In software deployment, an **environment** or **tier** is a computer system or set of systems in which a computer program or software component is deployed and executed.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] This structured release management process allows phased deployment (rollout), testing, and rollback in case of problems.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Environments may vary significantly in size: the development environment is typically an individual developer's workstation, while the production environment may be a network of many geographically distributed machines in data centers, or virtual machines in cloud computing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Code, data, and configuration may be deployed in parallel, and need not connect to the corresponding tier—for example, pre-production code might connect to a production database.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Deployment architectures vary significantly, but, broadly, the tiers are bookended by starting at *development* (DEV) and ending at *production* (PROD).
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] A common 4-tier architecture is *development, testing, model, production* (DEV, TEST, MODL, PROD), with software being deployed to each in order.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Other common environments include Quality Control (QC), for acceptance testing; sandbox or experimental (EXP), for experiments that are not intended to proceed to production; and Disaster Recovery, to provide an immediate fallback in case of problems with production.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Another common architecture is development, testing, acceptance and production (DTAP).
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] This language is particularly suited for server programs, where servers run in a remote data center; for code that runs on an end user's device, such as applications (apps) or clients, one can refer to the user environment (USER) or local environment (LOCAL) instead.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Exact definitions and boundaries between environments vary – test may be considered part of dev, Acceptance may be considered part of test, part of stage, or be separate, etc.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The main tiers are progressed through in order, with new releases being deployed (*rolled out* or *pushed*) to each in turn.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Experimental and recovery tiers, if present, are outside this flow – experimental releases are terminal, while recovery is typically an old or duplicate version of production, deployed after production.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] In case of problems, one can *roll back* to the old release, most simply by pushing the old release as if it were a new release.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The last step, deploying to production ("pushing to prod") is the most sensitive, as any problems result in immediate user impact.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] For this is often handled differently, at least being monitored more carefully, and in some cases having phased rollout or only requiring flipping a switch, allowing rapid rollback.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] It is best to avoid a name like Quality Assurance (QA); QA doesn’t mean software testing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Testing is important, but it is different from QA.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Sometimes deployment is done outside of this regular process, primarily to provide urgent or relatively minor changes, without requiring a full release.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] This may consist of a single patch, a large service pack, or a small hotfix.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The table below describes a finely-divided list of tiers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The development environment (dev) is the environment in which changes to software are developed, most simply an individual developer's workstation.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The environment on an individual workstation, in which changes are worked on and tried out, may be referred to as the *local environment* or a sandbox.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The purpose of the test environment is to allow human testers to exercise new and changed code via either automated checks or non-automated techniques.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] After the developer accepts the new code and configurations through unit testing in the development environment, the items are moved to one or more test environments.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Upon test failure, the test environment can remove the faulty code from the test platforms, contact the responsible developer, and provide detailed test and result logs.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] If all tests pass, the test environment or a continuous integration framework controlling the tests can automatically promote the code to the next deployment environment.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Different types of testing suggest different types of test environments, some or all of which may be virtualized to allow rapid, parallel testing to take place.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] For example, automated user interface tests may occur across several virtual operating systems and displays (real or virtual).
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Performance tests may require a normalized physical baseline hardware configuration, so that performance test results can be compared over time.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Availability or durability testing may depend on failure simulators in virtual hardware and virtual networks.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Tests may be serial (one after the other) or parallel (some or all at once) depending on the sophistication of the test environment.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] A significant goal for agile and other high-productivity software development practices is reducing the time from software design or specification to delivery in production.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Highly automated and parallelized test environments are important contributors to rapid software development.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] A stage, staging or pre-production environment is an environment for testing that exactly resembles a production environment.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] It seeks to mirror an actual production environment as closely as possible and may connect to other production services and data, such as databases.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] For example, servers will be run on remote machines, rather than locally (as on a developer's workstation during dev, or on a single test machine during the test), which tests the effects of networking on the system.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The primary use of a staging environment is to test all the installation/configuration/migration scripts and procedures before they're applied to a production environment.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] This ensures all major and minor upgrades to a production environment are completed reliably, without errors, and in a minimum of time.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Another important use of staging is performance testing, particularly load testing, as this is often sensitive to the environment.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Staging is also used by some organizations to preview new features to select customers or to validate integrations with live versions of external dependencies.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] The production environment is also known as *live*, particularly for servers, as it is the environment that users directly interact with.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Deploying to production is the most sensitive step; it may be done by deploying new code directly (overwriting old code, so only one copy is present at a time), or by deploying a configuration change.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] These in turn may be done all at once or gradually, in phases.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] When deploying a new release to production, rather than immediately deploying to all instances or users, it may be deployed to a single instance or fraction of users first, and then either deployed to all or gradually deployed in phases, in order to catch any last-minute problems.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] This is similar to staging, except actually done in production, and is referred to as a *canary release*, by analogy with coal mining.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] This adds complexity due to multiple releases being run simultaneously, and is thus usually over quickly, to avoid compatibility problems.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Development, Staging and Production are known and documented environment variables in ASP.NET Core.
[src:blue-green-deployment/deployment-environment] Depending on the defined variable, different code is executed and content rendered, and different security and debug settings are applied.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:blue-green-deployment/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
