[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The **software release life cycle** is the process of developing, testing, and distributing a software product (e.g., an operating system).
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] It typically consists of several stages, such as pre-alpha, alpha, beta, and release candidate, before the final version, or "gold", is released to the public.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to the early stages of development, when the software is still being designed and built.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha testing is the first phase of formal testing, during which the software is tested internally using white-box techniques.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Beta testing is the next phase, in which the software is tested by a larger group of users, typically outside the organization that developed it.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The beta phase is focused on reducing impacts on users and may include usability testing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] After beta testing, the software may go through one or more release candidate phases, in which it is refined and tested further, before the final version is released.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Some software, particularly in the internet and technology industries, is released in a perpetual beta state, meaning that it is continuously being updated and improved, and is never considered to be a fully completed product.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] This approach allows for a more agile development process and enables the software to be released and used by users earlier in the development cycle.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to all activities performed during the software project before formal testing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] These activities can include requirements analysis, software design, software development, and unit testing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] In typical open source development, there are several types of pre-alpha versions.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] *Milestone* versions include specific sets of functions and are released as soon as the feature is complete.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase of the release life cycle is the first phase of software testing (alpha is the first letter of the Greek alphabet, used as the number 1).
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] In this phase, developers generally test the software using white-box techniques.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Additional validation is then performed using black-box or gray-box techniques, by another testing team.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Moving to black-box testing inside the organization is known as *alpha release*.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software is not thoroughly tested by the developer before it is released to customers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may contain serious errors, and any resulting instability could cause crashes or data loss.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may not contain all of the features that are planned for the final version.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] In general, external availability of alpha software is uncommon for proprietary software, while open source software often has publicly available alpha versions.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase usually ends with a feature freeze, indicating that no more features will be added to the software.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] At this time, the software is said to be feature-complete.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] A beta test is carried out following acceptance testing at the supplier's site (the alpha test) and immediately before the general release of the software as a product.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] A **feature-complete** (FC) version of a piece of software has all of its planned or primary features implemented but is not yet final due to bugs, performance or stability issues.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] This occurs at the end of alpha testing in development.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Usually, feature-complete software still has to undergo beta testing and bug fixing, as well as performance or stability enhancement before it can go to release candidate, and finally gold status.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Beta, named after the second letter of the Greek alphabet, is the software development phase following alpha.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] A beta phase generally begins when the software is feature-complete but likely to contain several known or unknown bugs.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Software in the beta phase will generally have many more bugs in it than completed software and speed or performance issues, and may still cause crashes or data loss.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The focus of beta testing is reducing impacts on users, often incorporating usability testing.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The process of delivering a beta version to the users is called *beta release* and is typically the first time that the software is available outside the organization that developed it.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Software beta releases can be either open or closed, depending on whether they are openly available or only available to a limited audience.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Beta version software is often useful for demonstrations and previews within an organization and to prospective customers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Some developers refer to this stage as a *preview*, *preview release*, *prototype*, *technical preview* or *technology preview* (*TP*).
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is kept in so-called *perpetual beta*, where new features are continually added to the software without establishing a final "stable" release.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] As the Internet has facilitated the rapid and inexpensive distribution of software, companies have begun to take a looser approach to the use of the word *beta*.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] A *release candidate* (*RC*), also known as gamma testing or "going silver", is a beta version with the potential to be a stable product, which is ready to release unless significant bugs emerge.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] In this stage of product stabilization, all product features have been designed, coded, and tested through one or more beta cycles with no known showstopper-class bugs.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] A release is called *code complete* when the development team agrees that no entirely new source code will be added to this release.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] There could still be source code changes to fix defects, changes to documentation and data files, and peripheral code for test cases or utilities.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Also called *production release*, the *stable release* is the last *release candidate* (*RC*) which has passed all stages of verification and tests.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Any known remaining bugs are considered acceptable.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Linux distributions like Debian) also have *long-term support* (*LTS*) releases which are based on full releases that have already been tried and tested and receive only security updates.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Once released, the software is generally known as a "stable release".
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The formal term often depends on the method of release: physical media, online release, or a web application.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Usually the released software is assigned an official version name or version number.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] (Pre-release software may or may not have a separate internal project code name or internal version number).
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The term "release to manufacturing" (RTM), also known as "going gold", is a term used when a software product is ready to be delivered.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] This build may be digitally signed, allowing the end user to verify the integrity and authenticity of the software purchase.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The RTM build is known as the "gold master" or GM is sent for mass duplication or disc replication if applicable.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The terminology is taken from the audio record-making industry, specifically the process of mastering.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] RTM precedes general availability (GA) when the product is released to the public.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] A golden master build (GM) is typically the final build of a piece of software in the beta stages for developers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Typically, for iOS, it is the final build before a major release, however, there have been a few exceptions.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] RTM could also mean in other contexts that the software has been delivered or released to a client or customer for installation or distribution to the related hardware end user computers or machines.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The term does *not* define the delivery mechanism or volume; it only states that the quality is sufficient for mass distribution.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The deliverable from the engineering organization is frequently in the form of a golden master media used for duplication or to produce the image for the web.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] During its supported lifetime, the software is sometimes subjected to service releases, patches or service packs, sometimes also called "interim releases" or "maintenance releases" (MR).
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] For example, Microsoft released three major service packs for the 32-bit editions of Windows XP and two service packs for the 64-bit editions.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Such service releases contain a collection of updates, fixes, and enhancements, delivered in the form of a single installable package.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is released with the expectation of regular support.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Classes of software that generally involve protracted support as the norm include anti-virus suites and massively multiplayer online games.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Continuing with this Windows XP example, Microsoft did offer paid updates for five more years after the end of extended support.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] This means that support ended on April 8, 2019.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] After the end-of-life date, the developer will usually not implement any new features, fix existing defects, bugs, or vulnerabilities (whether known before that date or not), or provide any support for the product.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] If the developer wishes, they may release the source code, so that the platform may be maintained by volunteers.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Usage of the "alpha/beta" test terminology originated at IBM.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Similar terminologies for IBM's software development were used by people involved with IBM from at least the 1950s (and probably earlier).
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] "A" test was the verification of a new product before the public announcement.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The "B" test was the verification before releasing the product to be manufactured.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The "C" test was the final test before the general availability of the product.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] As software became a significant part of IBM's offerings, the alpha test terminology was used to denote the pre-announcement test and the beta test was used to show product readiness for general availability.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Martin Belsky, a manager on some of IBM's earlier software projects claimed to have invented the terminology.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] IBM dropped the alpha/beta terminology during the 1960s, but by then it had received fairly wide notice.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] The usage of "beta test" to refer to testing done by customers was not done in IBM.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Major public betas developed afterward, with early customers having purchased a "pioneer edition" of the WordVision word processor for the IBM PC for $49.95.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] In 1984, Stephen Manes wrote that "in a brilliant marketing coup, Bruce and James Program Publishers managed to get people to *pay* for the privilege of testing the product." In September 2000, a *boxed version* of Apple's Mac OS X Public Beta operating system was released.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Between September 2005 and May 2006, Microsoft released *community technology preview*s (*CTP*s) for Windows Vista.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] From 2009 to 2011, *Minecraft* was in public beta.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] In February 2005, ZDNet published an article about the phenomenon of a beta version often staying for years and being used as if it were at the production level.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] It noted that Gmail and Google News, for example, had been in beta for a long time although widely used; Google News left beta in January 2006, followed by Google Apps (now named Google Workspace), including Gmail, in July 2009.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] Since the introduction of Windows 8, Microsoft has called pre-release software a *preview* rather than *beta*.
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] All pre-release builds released through the Windows Insider Program launched in 2014 are termed "Insider Preview builds".
[src:blue-green-deployment/software-release-life-cycle] "Beta" may also indicate something more like a release candidate, or as a form of time-limited demo, or marketing technique.
